snippet.textDisplay:
At this point wouldnt it just be easier to add a giant water reservoir on top of the pc? the biggest heat ramps get absorbed by the aluminum case, until it gets really toasty (60-70 degrees). Then a copper reservoir with lets say 200 liters of water cools this down). To bring 200L of water up to 60-80 degrees, you need a lot of energy and a lot of time. before that happens, the computer surely is shut down. over night, the water cools down, also supported by the still very warm case and its fins. in the morning, everything is pretty much ambient again.

I really dont get it. its just a stupid way of getting more material to absorb the heat. the duration until "really hot" is scaling with material. so best case = more metal? whats the point?
I know people like these want to to be silent and all, but it would be just so much more efficient with just one or two giant very low RPM fans. or the big water tank. or a combination of that. for a 1000$ you can basically make a waterloop that is almost silent and so much more efficient/cool.
